    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Review velocity</strong> is the rate at which a business receives new online reviews over time — typically measured as reviews per week or month. Google considers review recency and frequency as local ranking signals. A business with 500 older reviews signals less activity than one with 120 recent reviews receiving 10 monthly.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Target velocity</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5-15 reviews/month</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Consumer recency threshold</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">73% of consumers consider reviews older than 3 months irrelevant (BrightLocal). Google's algorithm agrees — review recency is a growing ranking signal. A one-time review campaign that generated 50 reviews two years ago is now actively working against you as your stalled profile signals a less active business than competitors earning reviews consistently.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is review velocity?</h2>
        <p>Review velocity tracks how quickly businesses accumulate new reviews across platforms — Google, Yelp, Facebook, and industry-specific sites. It answers the question: "How many new reviews are you earning each week or month?"</p>
        <p>Velocity is distinct from total review count. A business with 500 reviews all from 2022 has high count but zero current velocity. A competitor with 120 reviews earning 10-15 per month has lower count but far stronger recency signals.</p>
        <p>Whitespark's Local Search Ranking Factors research identifies review recency as a growing ranking factor, with businesses maintaining consistent velocity ranking 2-3 positions higher in local packs than those with stalled profiles.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why recency beats total count</div>
          <p>Google's local algorithm prioritises businesses that are actively serving customers <em>right now</em>. A consistent stream of recent reviews signals an active, healthy business. Stalled review profiles — regardless of total count — signal reduced customer activity to the algorithm.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why review velocity matters for local SEO rankings</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Freshness signal.</strong> Google prioritises recent reviews over older content. Reviews from the past 30-90 days carry more ranking weight than reviews from 2+ years ago.</li>
          <li><strong>Consumer trust.</strong> 73% of consumers consider reviews older than 3 months irrelevant when making purchasing decisions (BrightLocal). High total count with no recent reviews triggers scepticism.</li>
          <li><strong>Ranking momentum.</strong> Faster-growing review profiles outrank competitors with similar total counts. Velocity creates compound ranking advantage over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Natural pattern detection.</strong> Consistent velocity of 5-10 reviews per month appears organic. Sudden spikes — 50 reviews in one week — trigger Google's spam detection algorithms and can result in review removal.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive differentiation.</strong> If the top 3 local competitors average 15 reviews per month and you average 2, the gap compounds. Six months later, you're 78 reviews behind on recency signal alone.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to measure and build review velocity</h2>

        <h3>Measuring velocity</h3>
        <p>Track monthly review count over a rolling 12-week window. Compare your velocity against your top 3 local competitors using BrightLocal, Whitespark Local Citation Finder, or manual monthly tracking.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Monthly velocity measurement</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Your business:</span> <span class="uf-new">8 new Google reviews in June</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Competitor A:</span> <span class="uf-old">22 new Google reviews in June</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Competitor B:</span> <span class="uf-old">15 new Google reviews in June</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Competitor C:</span> <span class="uf-new">6 new Google reviews in June</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Market average: 12.75/month — you need to close the gap</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Building sustainable velocity</h3>
        <p>Implement automated review requests triggered by service completion — not monthly email campaigns. Triggers tied to individual transactions distribute requests naturally across the month, creating the gradual, consistent pattern Google identifies as organic.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Review velocity benchmarks by business type</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
