        <h2 id="examples">Real review velocity examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — dental practice domination</h3>
        <p>A dental practice implemented automated post-appointment SMS review requests within 2 hours of each visit closure. Generating 3 new reviews weekly, they accumulated 150+ recent reviews within 12 months while their top competitor stagnated at 40 total reviews with no active generation system. The practice moved from position 4 to positions 1-2 in the local pack for their primary keywords.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — seasonal restaurant</h3>
        <p>A restaurant generating 20 monthly reviews in summer and 8 in winter worried about velocity inconsistency. Analysis showed the seasonal variation tracked perfectly with actual customer volume — Google's algorithm treats natural seasonal patterns as organic. Forcing artificial velocity in slow months with incentivised reviews actually triggered spam detection and led to review removals.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Review velocity vs. total review count — which matters more?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Total review count</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Establishes credibility baseline</li>
              <li>Visible in Google Business Profile summary</li>
              <li>Influences consumer trust on first impression</li>
              <li>Older reviews still add to aggregate signal</li>
              <li>Foundational — you need both count and velocity</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Review velocity</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Signals active, current customer base</li>
              <li>Directly tied to review recency algorithm factor</li>
              <li>Compounds ranking advantage month over month</li>
              <li>Prevents competitor catch-up</li>
              <li>Momentum — harder to replicate quickly</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for building review velocity</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Automate requests at service completion.</strong> Build review requests into your operational workflow — appointment close, transaction confirm, or project delivery. Manual campaigns are inconsistent; automation is consistent.</li>
          <li><strong>Use SMS, not email.</strong> Text-based review requests convert 2-3x better than email equivalents for most service businesses. Response rates drop significantly after the first hour.</li>
          <li><strong>Request within 24 hours.</strong> The first 24 hours post-service have the highest completion rates. Delay to 48+ hours and completion rates drop by 40-60%.</li>
          <li><strong>Distribute across platforms.</strong> Don't send all requests to Google only. Spread requests across Google, Yelp, and Facebook to build platform diversity alongside velocity.</li>
          <li><strong>Never bulk blast.</strong> Sending 50 requests simultaneously produces an unnatural velocity spike. Spread requests over days and weeks to match organic patterns.</li>
          <li><strong>Track competitor velocity monthly.</strong> Monitor how many reviews your top 3 competitors earned last month. Your target should be at or above the market average.</li>
          <li><strong>Measure by platform, not just total.</strong> Google velocity and Yelp velocity are separate signals. Track and manage both independently.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — the one-time campaign trap</div>
          <p>Many businesses run a single review campaign, collect 40-60 reviews, then stop. Within 90 days, the recency signal has decayed. Within 6 months, competitors with consistent monthly generation are outranking them on velocity signals alone. Review generation is an always-on system, not a campaign.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common review velocity mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sudden spikes.</strong> 30 reviews in one day triggers spam detection. Google's algorithm can demote or remove reviews that arrive in unnatural batches.</li>
          <li><strong>Buying reviews from farms.</strong> Review farms produce geographically inconsistent reviewers and unnaturally similar review text. Google's detection removes them, often with penalties.</li>
          <li><strong>Stopping after a successful campaign.</strong> Velocity is momentum. Stopping means losing recency signal within 60-90 days regardless of total count.</li>
          <li><strong>Only tracking Google.</strong> Yelp, Facebook, and industry sites all feed into local prominence. Monitoring only one platform misses the full velocity picture.</li>
          <li><strong>Not adjusting for seasonal patterns.</strong> Forcing artificial high velocity in slow seasons can look unnatural. Track velocity relative to actual customer volume.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring competitors' velocity.</strong> Your target velocity should be set relative to your market, not an arbitrary absolute number.</li>
        </ul>

